  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve red wine at room temperature with steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">"Room temperature" for red wine means 60-65°F, not modern room temperature of 70-72°F. Serve full-bodied reds like Cabernet Sauvignon slightly cooler than you might think – around 62-65°F brings out the fruit flavors while maintaining structure. Lighter reds like Pinot Noir should be served even cooler, around 58-62°F, to preserve their delicate aromatics alongside your steak.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair white wine with steak successfully?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely! Full-bodied, oaked white wines like Chardonnay from Burgundy or California work beautifully with lighter preparations like grilled fish or chicken, but can also complement pork tenderloin. For actual beef steak, try a rich Viognier or white Rhône blend with herb-crusted preparations. The key is matching the wine's weight and intensity to the cooking method and sauce rather than just the protein.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing wine with steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is ignoring the sauce and preparation method, focusing only on the meat itself. A delicate filet with béarnaise sauce needs a different wine than the same cut with chimichurri or peppercorn sauce. The sauce, seasoning, and cooking method often have more impact on the pairing than the cut of beef, so always consider the complete dish when selecting your wine.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is steak wine pairing good for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Steak pairings are excellent for beginners because the classic combinations are very forgiving and showcase why certain pairings work. The protein and fat in steak soften harsh tannins, making bold red wines more approachable than they would be on their own. Start with proven combinations like ribeye with Cabernet Sauvignon or strip steak with Malbec – these pairings demonstrate fundamental principles you can apply to other foods.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Do I need expensive wine for a good steak pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Not at all! Many excellent steak wines exist in the $15-25 range, including Argentine Malbec, Spanish Tempranillo, and Washington State Cabernet Sauvignon. The key is finding wines with good structure and concentration rather than chasing prestigious labels. A well-made $20 Côtes du Rhône often pairs better with grilled steak than a $100 wine that's too delicate or unbalanced for the pairing.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How far in advance should I open red wine before serving with steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Young, tannic reds benefit from 30-60 minutes of breathing time to soften harsh edges before pairing with steak. Older wines (10+ years) should be opened just before serving to preserve their delicate aromatics. Use a decanter for wines under 5 years old, simply removing the cork for mature bottles. The meat's richness will help integrate any remaining tannins even without extensive aeration.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibeled text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine alternatives work well with steak for non-wine drinkers?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Full-bodied beer like porter or stout provides similar richness and complements grilled flavors beautifully with steak. Aged spirits like bourbon or cognac, served neat or on the rocks, offer the complexity and intensity that match well with red meat. For non-alcoholic options, try grape juice-based mocktails with herbs like rosemary, or strong black tea with tannins that mimic wine's structure.</p>
